@node intro "JPBoot help-guide v1.0"
@{b}JPBoot help-guide v1.0@{ub}

@{b}What is this?@{ub}


JPBoot's primary function is just a startup-selector.  So,  when you want to
use more than one startup-sequence file, this program allows you to do so.

Second, you can use password protection.  At  every  startup JPBoot asks you
valid password,  and if it gets one,  it lets you to continue booting. There
you can use many different login-names and passwords.  Also  'visitors'  are
welcome,  so  other  people  without valid login and password can enter into
your computer with some restrictions. Normal users (not visitors) can be log
in either level 1 (root) or level 2 (normal user).  Restrictions can also be
set for normal users. See @{"JPBoot.prefs" link prefs} details for restrictions.

This protection is NOT perfect in any way. Anyone who knows what he is doing
can easily hack his way through.  This  protection is just there to keep you
little sister away for you files. And maybe avoid accidents (at least I have
more than once wiped away half of my Workbench partition  by  accident,  and
that is not fun, I can tell you).

And last, JPBoot offers you a VERY nice bootpicture, which will be displayed
during booting. Take a look at the screenshots!

Unfortunately, bootpicture works only on machines with AGA chipset or above.

JPboot is not a hack of any kind.  All functions works  system-friendly,  no
patches will be installed.
@endnode


@node issue "JPBoot help-guide v1.0"
@{b}JPBoot help-guide v1.0@{ub}

@{b}How to use it?@{ub}


@{b}JPBoot:@{ub}

	Lets assume that  you  have  installed  it  correctly.  If  you  use
	@{"ASKUSERNAME" link prefs} option, first  thing  you  see  at  bootup  is  'Please
	type in your login' window. There you  must  type  your  login-name.
	When done, just press enter,  and it asks a password for that login.
	Type your password, press enter, and if it was correct, boot-process
	will continue. Otherwise you see 'Please type in your login'  window
	again.

	If @{"ALLOWVISITORS" link prefs} option is on, you  can  type  'visitor'  in  login
	prompt and just enter in password prompt. If you do, you have logged
	in as a visitor.  Visitor cannot select  between  separate startups,
	JPBoot executes always 'S:Startup-Sequence.original'  for  visitors.
	Also restrictions takes  effect  now  if  you  dont  use  @{"AFTERLOCK" link prefs}
	option. See @{"JPBoot.prefs" link prefs} for details.

	If 'S:Bootmenu' directory  is  empty,  JPBoot  executes  'S:Startup-
	sequence.original' now. But if you have some startups in there, next
	thing you see  is  startup-selector.  Choose  startup  you  want  to
	with mouse or keyboard. Mouse works  with  usual  manner,  keys  are
	here:

	    Arrow up        - move selector up
	    Arrow down      - move selector down
	    Enter           - select it
	    ESC             - quit

	Please note about the ESC-key. If you  press  it,  JPBoot  will  not
	execute any startups. It just quits and opens a Shell-window.

	And now, while startup is running,  you see a bootpicture  (only  if
	you have enabled @{"USESCREEN" link prefs} option).

	At last, in ENV: directory appears file named  USER.  This  is  USER
	environment-variable which contains your login name or  VISITOR.  If
	@{"AFTERLOCK" link prefs} is on, desired devices will be locked now.


@{b}Adduser:@{ub}

	(Root user only)

	With this program you can add user who can log in.  Just simply type
	desired login-name and password there, then  press  OK.  To  cancel,
	press close-gadget.

	Note about the 'Root?' option. IF YOU ARE MAKING  FIRST  USER,  THIS
	OPTION !MUST! BE TURNED ON! IF IT IS NOT, YOU CANNOT ADD MORE USERS,
	BECAUSE YOU CANNOT LOG IN AS A ROOT!!

	Ofcourse you can make more than just one root if you like.


@{b}Removeuser:@{ub}

	(Root user only)

	Works exactly same manner than Adduser, but removes  user  from  the
	'S:JPBoot.users' file.


@{b}Checkuser:@{ub}

	With checkuser you  can  check  the  userlevel.  If  you  just  type
	'Checkuser',   it  creates  environment-variable  named  'USERLEVEL'
	which contains number as explained here:

	 1 for root,
	 2 for normal user,
	 3 for visitor.

	You can also use this program with shell-scripts. Take a look at the
	example here:
	--------------------------------------------------------------------

	    C:Checkuser
	    IF $USERLEVEL EQ 3                  ; Check if visitor?
		C:RequestChoice >ENV:rcnum "AmigaOS" "Visitors cannot start Linux." "OK"
		Quit                            ; Was visitor, quit.
	    EndIF

	    C:RequestChoice >ENV:rcnum "AmigaOS" "Start Linux?" "Yes" "Cancel"
	    IF $rcnum EQ 1
		SYS:Multi-OS/Linux/Linux        ; Start Linux.
		Quit
	    EndIF

	--------------------------------------------------------------------
	So as you can see, only root and normal user can start Linux now.


@{b}Login:@{ub}

	If you need to change your login-level, you can do it  with  'Login'
	command.  Just type here new login and password.  Also  locks  takes
	effect if you are logging in to root->normal user, or if you logging
	as normal user->root, locks will be removed if there is any.

	To cancel action, just press the close-gadget.


@{b}Showusers:@{ub}

	This is simple.  Just  type  'Showusers' from Shell, and it displays
	all login names. For example, output stream may look like this:

	    Current users:

		    - Root (root)
		    - Jani

	Ofcourse passwords are not listed here.

	Note about  '(root)'  after the first name.  This  means  that  this
	user is a root user.


@{b}WhoAmI:@{ub}

	Another simple one. There is no parameters, just type 'WhoAmI',  and
	you see your current login-level.
@endnode


@node install "JPBoot help-guide v1.0"
@{b}JPBoot help-guide v1.0@{ub}

@{b}Installation@{ub}


Be sure you read ALL of this guide before you start installing!


There is no install-script for this, so just do the following:

0.      Backup your original startup-sequence.


1.      Copy   files   'JPBoot',   'Adduser',   'Removeuser',   'Checkuser',
	'Login',  'Showusers'   and   'WhoAmI'   in   C:   directory,   file
	JPBoot.prefs in S: directory and this guide to HELP: directory.


2.      Make new directory 'S:Bootmenu'


3.      Rename your startup-sequence as startup-sequence.original


4.      Load your favour ASCII-editor and make new startup-sequence.
	It should look like this for now, edit it later:
	--------------------------------------------------------------------

	    C:SetPatch QUIET

	    C:Assign >NIL: T: RAM:
	    C:Assign >NIL: ENV: RAM:
	    C:Assign >NIL: FONTS: SYS:Fonts

	    C:List >NIL: DEVS:Monitors/~(#?.info|VGAOnly) TO T:Monitors LFORMAT "DEVS:Monitors/%s"
	    C:Execute T:Monitors

	    C:JPBoot

	    EndCLI >NIL:

	--------------------------------------------------------------------
	With this startup, your computer should boot up properly.


5.      Remove  'SetPatch'  and  'List >NIL: DEVS:Monitors...'  commands  in
	startup-sequence.original (They must then be in startup-sequence).


6.      Edit  'S:JPBoot.prefs'.  Its  advised  to   disable   options   like
	@{"ASKUSERNAME" link prefs},  @{"ALLOWVISITORS" link prefs}  and  @{"SAVETIME" link prefs}  for  now.   Just  set
	these to N. Also  proper  screenmode  can  be  set  now. Please look
	at the @{"Screenmodes" link modes} table.

	Also if you use computer with OCS or ECS  chips,  you  must  disable
	@{"USESCREEN" link prefs} option too. Then dont bother to set the screenmode.


7.      Try to reboot. If all was fine, go in next section.


8.      Now you need to add yourself an user, so run 'Adduser' command. Type
	there your login and password. If you are making first user, 'Root?'
	option MUST be turned on! If it is not,  you  cannot add more users,
	because you cannot log in as a Root!


9.      Now  you  can  enable  options  @{"ASKUSERNAME" link prefs},  @{"ALLOWVISITORS" link prefs},   and
	@{"SAVETIME" link prefs} if you want.

	Also edit  @{"VISITORLOCK" link prefs}  and  @{"NORMALLOCK" link prefs}  options  to  follow  your
	configuration.


10.     Now  you  can  make  more  startup-sequences,  and  place  them   in
	'S:Bootmenu' directory.

	Please look at my startups (mystartups.lha) if you are confused with
	startups.


11.     Now you are done. Happy booting!
@endnode


@node requires "JPBoot help-guide v1.0"
@{b}JPBoot help-guide v1.0@{ub}

@{b}Requirements@{ub}


	- Amiga compatible computer with MC680x0 processor

	- AmigaDOS 3.0 (v39) or higher

	- Harddisk space approx. 200K

	- Some memory (100K should be enough)

	- AGA or better display is STRONGLY recommended

	- Standard   AmigaDOS  commands  Execute,  Lock,  Date,  Setenv  and
	  NewShell available in C: or residents.
@endnode


@node problems "JPBoot help-guide v1.0"
@{b}JPBoot help-guide v1.0@{ub}

@{b}Problems@{ub}


There is no any known bugs,  but  some  problems  may  occur  if you use own
screen for JPBoot. Usually these display problems causes because of display-
drivers.  So  remember;  if you are using some other than default (PAL/NTSC)
display,  you  MUST  load  current  displaydriver  before  you start JPBoot.
Otherwise it wont work properly.  Also,  if  you use OCS or ECS chipset, you
cannot use JPBoot's own screen.  OCS  and  ECS  chips has too few colors for
this,  and only solution is disabling @{"USESCREEN" link prefs} option in JPBoot.prefs-file
on OCS and ECS machines (I see no point to support these over 10  years  old
chips anyway). See @{"JPBoot.prefs" link prefs} for details.

JPBoot uses external AmigaDOS  commands  Execute,  Lock,  Date,  Setenv  and
NewShell.  If one is missing,  you can expect problems.  At  least  AmigaDOS
3.0 has Setenv and NewShell commands in  ROM,  so  Execute,  Lock  and  Date
should be available in C: directory.

Please note this well: When you are creating new login  name  with  Adduser-
program, you may think using names like 'Päivi', 'Jaçues'  or  'Rueslĺtten'.

So, whats the problem then, I hear you ask? Well, the  problem  is  ofcourse
foreign characters in these names (ä, ç and ĺ). When you type in your  login
(or password) you have your local keymap loaded, lets  say  this  map  is  S
(swedish). So, when it is loaded, you can use characters like ä,  ö  and  ĺ.
But when JPBoot asks your login and password names (in the beginning of boot
process), you cannot use these characters because this keymap is not  loaded
yet. If you then try to press 'ö'-button, you just get  ';'  character,  and
this ofcourse does not work. So then is very advised to use only  'a-z'  and
'A-Z' characters in login and password names.
@endnode


